Oxford English Dictionary said it has added 29 Nigerian words and expressions in the January updates to the dictionary. Oxford English Dictionary revealed in a blogspost posted on the dictionary’s website that the 29 Nigerian entries form part of the more than 550 new words, senses, and sub-entries added to the Oxford English Dictionary Oxford English Dictionary ’s World English editor, Danica Salazar, said: “The majority of these new additions are either borrowings from Nigerian languages, or unique Nigerian coinages that have only begun to be used in English in the second half of the twentieth century, mostly in the 1970s and 1980s.” ‘Next tomorrow,’ is one of the new entries into the dictionary. The expression is regarded as the oldest among the over 25 uniquely Nigerian words/expressions. According to Salazar, ‘next tomorrow’ was first used in written English as a noun in 1953, and as an adverb in 1964. ALSO READ: Guber election: Supreme Court upholds Ortom, Fintiri’s election Kannywood, which refers to the film industry in northern Nigeria, is deemed the youngest among the lot. Malami’s position on Amotekun grossly misconceived As Ogun’s stellar cabinet takes off LCDA chairman promises to return all out-of-school children… Platform collapse: Death toll rises to 10 in Ethiopia Others such as ‘buka,’ ‘bukateria’ and ‘severally’ also made the dictionary. The full list of the new entries is below: ALSO READ: PDP hails Supreme Court judgment on Sokoto, Bauchi, Benue, Adamawa You can see the full list of words to be added in this Oxford English Dictionary update here. The Oxford English Dictionary publishes four updates a year. The next update will be added to the dictionary in March 2020. SHOCKING LIFE STORY!!! Abuja Man reveals (FREE) secret Fruits that Increased his Manh0d size and Lasting Power in just 7days… CLICK HERE TO GET IT!!! STAY STRONGER, LONGER AND SATISFY MADAM LIKE NEVER BEFORE WITH THIS NATURAL SUPPLEMENTS WITH NO SIDE EFFECTS. CLICK NOW. CLICK HERE 